const ROUTE_EXTRAS={
 baker_cd:{access:{fees:"Northwest Forest Pass (about $5/day or annual) to park at Heliotrope Ridge.",closure:"Road and upper mountain are snowbound into spring; the standard season is late May to September.",rules:"Mt Baker–Snoqualmie National Forest / Mount Baker Wilderness: self-issue climbing permit at the trailhead, pack out all waste (blue bags on the glacier), group-size limits apply."},comms:{coverage:"none",note:"No reliable cell service on the mountain. Carry a satellite messenger or PLB and leave a trip plan."},retreat:"Above the toe of the Coleman, every retreat is a roped glacier descent - never solo down through crevasse terrain. Turn-around discipline is the whole game: set a hard time (commonly off the summit by 9 a.m.) and honor it regardless of how close the top looks. In a whiteout, navigate back along your wands and GPS track to the saddle and down to Hogsback; below the glacier toe it is a simple walk-off. Carry a crevasse-rescue kit and be practiced with it.",pairsWith:[]},kings_hf:{access:{fees:"Free.",closure:"Snow-bound roughly October to June; the standard season is July to September.",rules:"High Uintas Wilderness: groups capped at 14 (people and stock combined), no mechanized travel, pack out everything."},comms:{coverage:"none",note:"No service from Henrys Fork trailhead inward. Carry a satellite messenger or PLB."},retreat:"Non-technical the whole way, so retreat just means reversing your steps to lower, sheltered ground. The real bail trigger is weather: if cumulus is building or you hear thunder, get off the exposed summit ridge and Anderson Pass immediately and drop into the basin. Gunsight Pass and Dollar Lake are the natural regroup points. There is no cell service inland, so carry a satellite messenger or PLB.",pairsWith:[]},
 olympus_wf:{access:{fees:"Free.",closure:"Best spring through fall; shaded gullies can hold snow and ice into May.",rules:"Park considerately in the Olympus Cove neighborhood and stay on the established path - the lower approach skirts private property."},comms:{coverage:"good",note:"Strong signal across the slabs thanks to the valley below."},retreat:"The slab is low-angle enough to downclimb or reverse on belay if you bail mid-route, and intermediate ledges allow a single-rope retreat leaving a little gear. The bigger commitment is the walk-off, so if weather threatens, retreat before topping out rather than committing to the exposed ridge descent. Wasatch heat and storms build fast, so be off the upper slab early.",pairsWith:[]},
 angels_chains:{access:{fees:"$35 per vehicle (7-day Zion pass) or America the Beautiful.",closure:"Open year-round, though storms can ice up or close the chains in winter.",rules:"A permit is REQUIRED for the chains section (seasonal lottery on Recreation.gov). The park shuttle is mandatory most of the year to reach the Grotto trailhead."},comms:{coverage:"spotty",note:"Patchy down in the canyon; better on the exposed spine up high."},retreat:"Bailing is simple - turn around anywhere on the chains and walk back to Scout Lookout, which is both the natural decision point and the limit of travel without a permit. Do not get on the chains in rain, snow, or high wind, or when they are crowded; the sandstone gets slick and the exposure is unforgiving. If you are unsure at Scout Lookout, the view from there is excellent and stopping is no failure.",pairsWith:[]},
 lcc_schoolroom:{access:{fees:"Free.",closure:"Spring through fall; the canyon is plowed for skiing in winter and climbing access is limited by snow.",rules:"Salt Lake watershed: NO dogs anywhere in Little Cottonwood, no swimming or wading. Park only in established pullouts."},comms:{coverage:"good",note:"Reliable LTE through most of lower LCC."},retreat:"Low-angle and well-protected, so a mid-route bail is easy: build a gear anchor or use a station and lower or rappel off, leaving minimal gear. Because it is a popular beginner trad line, the main hazards are parties above you (rockfall) and traffic jams, not the climbing. If a storm rolls in, the 3rd-class walk-off from partway is often faster than rigging rappels.",pairsWith:[{id:"lcc_mexican_crack",note:"Classic hand crack just up-canyon - a great add-on for the day."}]},
 lcc_mexican_crack:{access:{fees:"Free.",closure:"Spring through fall; snow-dependent in winter.",rules:"Salt Lake watershed: no dogs, no swimming. Use established pullouts."},comms:{coverage:"good",note:"Reliable signal in the canyon."},retreat:"The bolted anchor atop the first pitch is a clean bail point - lower or rappel from it with no gear left behind, and lower on the route the easy terrain downclimbs readily. The crack seeps after rain and stays damp in the shade, so if it is wet, save it for a dry spell rather than forcing greasy jams.",pairsWith:[{id:"lcc_schoolroom",note:"Pair with this nearby multipitch for a fuller day."}]},
 lcc_hellgate_optimist:{access:{fees:"Free.",closure:"Spring through fall; snow-dependent in winter.",rules:"Salt Lake watershed: no dogs, no swimming. Established pullouts only."},comms:{coverage:"good",note:"Reliable signal at the Hellgate cliffs."},retreat:"Fully bolted, so bailing is just lowering from the highest bolt or the anchor - leave a carabiner if you cannot reach the chains. Consequences are low on a single-pitch sport route; the real factors are afternoon sun and heat on this aspect and occasional rockfall from the trail above. If you pump out, have your belayer lower you.",pairsWith:[{id:"lcc_hellgate_tingey",note:"Right next door on the same Hellgate cliff."}]},
 lcc_hellgate_tingey:{access:{fees:"Free.",closure:"Spring through fall; snow-dependent in winter.",rules:"Salt Lake watershed: no dogs, no swimming. Established pullouts only."},comms:{coverage:"good",note:"Reliable signal at the Hellgate cliffs."},retreat:"Bolted throughout, so retreat is trivial - lower from any bolt and leave a bail biner. On a hard project the bail is usually just taking and lowering between burns, not an emergency. Mind the heat and sun on the aspect, and watch for rockfall from parties or hikers above.",pairsWith:[{id:"lcc_hellgate_optimist",note:"Same cliff - easy to tick both in a session."}]},
 lcc_twisted:{access:{fees:"Free.",closure:"Spring through fall; best in cool, dry conditions.",rules:"Salt Lake watershed: no dogs, no swimming. Pack out chalk and tape."},comms:{coverage:"good",note:"Reliable signal at the boulders."},retreat:"Bailing off a boulder just means dropping to the pads, so your safety margin is pad coverage and a good spot, not a rope. The granite stays cold and can be damp in shade after storms - brush the holds and re-check the landing between attempts. If the top-out feels committing, stack pads under it and position a spotter.",pairsWith:[{id:"lcc_lances_dihedral",note:"Part of the same LCC circuit - short walk between."},{id:"lcc_copperhead",note:"Another nearby problem to round out the session."}]},
 lcc_lances_dihedral:{access:{fees:"Free.",closure:"Spring through fall; best in cool, dry conditions.",rules:"Salt Lake watershed: no dogs, no swimming. Pack out chalk and tape."},comms:{coverage:"good",note:"Reliable signal at the boulders."},retreat:"As with any boulder, retreat is a controlled drop to the pads - coverage and an attentive spotter are your protection. The dihedral stays greasy in the shade after wet weather, so wait for it to dry. If the committing finish is not there on the day, work the lower moves and save the top-out for when the pads and spot are dialed.",pairsWith:[{id:"lcc_twisted",note:"Same circuit, short walk."},{id:"lcc_copperhead",note:"Nearby problem."}]},
 lcc_copperhead:{access:{fees:"Free.",closure:"Spring through fall; best in cool, dry conditions.",rules:"Salt Lake watershed: no dogs, no swimming. Pack out chalk and tape."},comms:{coverage:"good",note:"Reliable signal at the boulders."},retreat:"On a hard highball, bailing means a clean drop to well-placed pads with a spotter ready - that landing is your only protection, so build it carefully. The crux is low but the top-out is the consequence; if the pads or the spot are not dialed, work the bottom and save the finish. Cold, dry granite climbs best - brush the holds and re-check the landing every burn.",pairsWith:[{id:"lcc_twisted",note:"Same circuit."},{id:"lcc_lances_dihedral",note:"Nearby problem."}]},
 bridalveil_falls:{access:{fees:"Free.",closure:"Ice forms roughly December to March and is highly condition-dependent; the falls can be unstable or out in warm spells.",rules:"Check current ice conditions and the avalanche advisory for the slopes above before committing."},comms:{coverage:"good",note:"Near the road and trail - reliable signal at the base."},retreat:"You can bail from most points by building a V-thread and rappelling, so carry extra cord and a threader. The overriding bail trigger is avalanche and warming: if the snowpack is loaded or the day heats up, retreat down-canyon at once, since both the climb and the approach sit under slide paths. Rapidly rising temps also rot the ice - if it turns wet and drippy, get off.",pairsWith:[]},
 octopussy:{access:{fees:"Free roadside parking on Hwy 24; arrive early, spots are limited.",closure:"Mixed and ice season is roughly December to March, condition-dependent.",rules:"Popular venue - climb efficiently and mind parties below while you're on lead."},comms:{coverage:"spotty",note:"In-and-out in the amphitheater; better up on the road."},retreat:"On the mixed roof you can lower or rappel off the highest bolt or anchor if you cannot link into the ice - leave a biner. The dagger's condition is the real bail decision: if it is detached, sun-baked, or sounds hollow, do not commit to it, and keep clear of the fall line while others climb. Cold, shaded conditions keep the hanging ice bonded, so bail if it is warming.",pairsWith:[]},
 washington_column_sf:{access:{fees:"$35 per vehicle (7-day Yosemite pass); peak-season entry reservations may apply.",closure:"Climbable most of the year; summer is hot, spring and fall are prime.",rules:"A wilderness permit is required to bivy on the wall. Pack out all waste using wag bags."},comms:{coverage:"none",note:"No service on the wall - leave an itinerary and carry a satellite device."},retreat:"From below Dinner Ledge, retreat is a series of rappels down the line - straightforward if you have tracked your stations. The Dinner Ledge bivy is the natural commitment point; above it, bailing means more involved rappels with the bag. The south-facing wall bakes in the afternoon, so manage water and time, and remember an early-pitch retreat is far easier than a high one.",pairsWith:[]}
};
